Andy (andrew.newcombe@dundee.ncr.com.uk) wrote:
: I'm going to buy a 486 PCI motherboard soon, and Intel seems to have the most 
: stable/best performing chipsets at the moment.  Can anyone tell me whether the 
: Saturn II offers any real world performance gains over the Aries chipset?  I 
: know it uses interleaved memory(two 72 pin simms at a time), but are the gains 
: really noticable? 

: And how about PCI transfers (with Video and SCSI), Will Saturn II be any faster 
: ?  

: I see Aries claims to work upto 50 MHz, so presumably is OK at 40, (or is that 
: 50  MHZ as in DX2-50?), where Saturn only mentions 33MHz. Does Saturn II work at 
: 40?

You might want to check your sources again.  I've got a "quick reference 
sheet" straight from the Intel fax-back service (800-628-2283 or 
916-356-3105 from the US or Canada, 24 hours a day) which specifies that 
the Aries chipset "supports full 32-bit Intel486 and OverDrive Processors 
data bus frequencies up to 33mhz" (don't blame me for the punctuation on 
that one).  Precisely the same comment appears under both the "Saturn" 
and "Saturn II" chipsets.  Perhaps the comment you saw was referring to a 
DX2/50 CPU (but then, why not specify a DX2/66?).  According to this 
quick reference guide, the Aries chipset includes a local bus IDE 
interface and up to 128MB of RAM, while the Saturn II has no IDE 
interface and supports up to 160MB of RAM.

I can comment from personal experience that the Saturn I (aka revision 2)
chipset is buggy.  On the J-Bond motherboard that I bought, I experienced
occasional system hangs under OS/2 when performing SCSI I/O.  These hangs
went away when I disabled the external cache.  I returned the J-Bond and 
purchased an Asus SP3G, which uses the Saturn II (aka revision 4) 
chipset, and no more SCSI hangs.  I've also heard that some vendors have 
fixes for the Saturn I bugs, but I can't comment on how well they work, 
if they work at all.  I've also heard, but also can't comment from 
personal experience, that the Aries chipset has bugs comparable to those 
in the Saturn I chipset, and that this chipset is generally used only in 
dual PCI/VLB boards, which (as a class, not just boards based on the 
Intel chipset) tend to include design compromises which slow down the 
performance of one or both busses.

After spending a week tracking down the bugs in the J-Bond board, my
advice is to buy something that uses the Saturn II chipset.  Since most
vendors have no idea what they've got, have them inspect (or inspect
yourself, if it's a local dealer) the board.  Look for the chip with the
numbers 82424 on it.  If those numbers are followed by "TX," it's a Saturn
I, revision 2 chipset; if they're followed by "ZX," it's a Saturn II,
revision 4 chipset.  (The 82423 chip will be followed by "TX" for both
chipsets, so be sure to look at the correct chip.)  As I mentioned, the
Asus SP3G uses the Saturn II chipset, and has been fairly stable for me so
far (only two days, though, so take this particular testimonial with a
grain of salt).  The older Asus SP3 uses the Saturn I chipset, though Asus
is one of the vendors claiming to have a fix.  Since the SP3G seems to
cost about the same as the SP3, though, I'd go with the former.  Both
boards include NCR-based SCSI controllers, IDE, 2.88MB floppy, 2 16550
serial, and parallel ports.  E-mail me if you want to know who sells these
boards, since I picked up a number of recommendations before getting mine. 

