andrew.newcombe@dundee.ncr.com (Andy) writes:

>Well,  the Saturn 2 boards I've seen use interleaved memory(requireing 2 32bit 
>simms),where  the Aries boards do not (just 1 32bit simm at a time). I assumed 
>this was down to the Chipset, but maybe not.

It is.

In the test the German mag C'T did a couple of months ago, they noted that
the Saturn always used interleaved memory access, while the cheaper Intel
chipset under review--I cannot remember if it was the Aries or not--could
use _both_ interleaved and non-interleaved, depending on the number of
DRAM banks available.  So the fact that you don't have to use pairs of
SIMMs doesn't exclude the possibility.

>It would go along with  Intel calling the Saturn the 'top performance',
>and the Aries the 'entry level' chipsets.

I remember that there were other differences, such as not using a separate
tag RAM & such.  The performance difference in that test was remarkably
slight; the difference between Intel and the rest of the pack was far
larger.  But again, I don't remember if the second chipset under review
was actually the Aries.  OTOH, if Intel has only two types, you can be
pretty sure it was ;^)

